Chapter 1
Cohren
4h30, Itanian time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Getting out of his bed silently, he put on his combat uniform, put on his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He put his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pouches, he left the barracks quietly, the sound of mud and crushed ice resonating under his boots.
He took out a lighter from his vest pocket and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before slowly opening the door. Last week, he had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He stopped using the pre-set alarm, half the time, it didn't work, because everything that came out of the speakers was a faint whistle.
"Wake them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic arriving on foot.
"Ouep", responded Cohren.
"What have you planned to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and equipped.
"Good morning", said Craith.
"What woke you up?", asked Cohren.
"Well, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secundo, the first shock troops standing are the first at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be".
"You're right, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and activated a switch. An alarm echoed inside the barracks, loud and screaming. He heard commotion inside and agitation.
"Good grief, Valturi," launched Nemic. "We would have thought they would have learned to get up at the same time as you, by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here made us do it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, once again, their group and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company was coming out en masse. Everyone had what they needed, personal items to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," Cohren said with a cheerful voice.
"Respectfully, chief, why do you insist on waking us up in this manner?" one of the shock troops' members, a corporal, asked.
"Because standard wake-up times are terrible. And because Daybreak isn't a morning person," Cohren replied.
"Make sure to have all your personal effects," he continued. As the first lieutenant and the commander's assistant, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to conduct the final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of shock troops, second army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a broken company, and Cohren didn't know what to think of his promotion as first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that motivated him.
Cothren and Nemic, the head of the first platoon, marched together under the light of the many illuminations of the advanced operational base, powered by generators. Most were painted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to fight them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?""
"An advanced operational base outside Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, pulling on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of fighting changes a man, and he fell silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," Nemic muttered. "All the news coming from this place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?""
"Amen, my brother," Cohren said, flicking his cigar butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're leaving with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Shaw has a lift for us?", Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought he'd be. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All units of Exodus Company, report to the west vehicle park when you're done. We're leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
About every few seconds, he received responses from squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-coms when they got here. All four had been close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like a lifetime ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were all squadron leaders then. But Craith was now commanding the second platoon for a week, after the previous commander, wounded by a Daybreak sniper, demobilized.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crew was busy, making sure their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked towards them, his normally cold face reflecting no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He says Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
